"García-Sellés C., Peña J.C., Martí G., Oller P., Martínez P.","WeMOI and NAOi influence on major avalanche activity in the Eastern Pyrenees",2010,"Cold Regions Science and Technology","64","2",,"137","145",,,10.1016/j.coldregions.2010.08.003,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77957861339&partnerID=40&md5=48169b4ec205e29c345fe91c8a275ecc","Geological Institute of Catalonia, Barcelona, Spain; Meteorological Service of Catalonia, Spain","García-Sellés, C., Geological Institute of Catalonia, Barcelona, Spain; Peña, J.C., Meteorological Service of Catalonia, Spain; Martí, G., Geological Institute of Catalonia, Barcelona, Spain; Oller, P., Geological Institute of Catalonia, Barcelona, Spain; Martínez, P., Geological Institute of Catalonia, Barcelona, Spain","Major avalanche episodes registered in the Eastern Pyrenees (north-eastern Iberian Peninsula) are correlated with both the North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO) and the Western Mediterranean Oscillation (WeMO). The NAO is one of the most important and recurrent patterns of atmospheric circulation variability in the Northern Hemisphere and affects the behaviour of surface temperatures and precipitation in Western Europe. The Western Mediterranean Oscillation index (WeMOi) controls intense precipitation in the eastern part of the Iberian Peninsula. The link between both indices and major avalanche activity is undertaken by applying a cumulative index. A link between avalanche activity and the NAO has been found in Iceland, but it has not been detected in areas closer to the Pyrenees, such as the French Alps. This paper examines the linkage to the NAO in an area further from the centres of the dipole than is the case for Iceland. Results show a significant negative correlation between major avalanche activity in the Eastern Pyrenees and both NAO index (NAOi) and WeMOi, which is even higher with the cumulative NAOi (CNI) and the cumulative WeMOi (CWI). The cumulative index reflects the cumulative effect of snow accumulation in the avalanche starting zones as precipitation is affected by the variations of NAOi and WeMOi. Consequently, the correlation is negative since it has been demonstrated that increased precipitation in the Eastern Pyrenees is linked to negative values of both low frequency patterns. Nevertheless, results from the diverse avalanche forecasting regions in the Eastern Pyrenees suggest a different response of avalanche activity to both indices, confirming the Pyrenees as a complex snow-climate boundary. Lastly, possible changes in avalanche activity in the coming decades may be suggested by the NAO evolution associated with global warming scenarios that are foreseen and the present interannual trend of the WeMOi. © 2010 Elsevier B.V.","Avalanches; Eastern Pyrenees; North Atlantic Oscillation; Western Mediterranean Oscillation","Atmospheric circulation variability; Avalanche forecasting; Avalanches; Cumulative effects; French Alps; Iberian Peninsula; Icelands; Intense precipitation; Interannual; Low frequency; NAO index; Negative correlation; Negative values; North Atlantic oscillations; Northern Hemispheres; Oscillation index; Pyrenees; Recurrent patterns; Snow accumulation; Surface temperatures; Western Europe; Western Mediterranean; Western Mediterranean Oscillation; Climatology; Global warming; Snow; Weather forecasting; Atmospheric pressure; annual variation; atmospheric circulation; avalanche; climate oscillation; correlation; global warming; North Atlantic Oscillation; Northern Hemisphere; precipitation intensity; snow; snow accumulation; snow cover; trend analysis; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (North); Iberian Peninsula; Mediterranean Sea; Mediterranean Sea (West); Pyrenees; Western Europe",,,,,,"Beniston, M., Rebetez, M., Regional behaviour of minimum temperatures in Switzerland for the period 1979-1993 (1996) Theoretical and Applied Climatology, 53, pp. 231-243. , Springer-Verlag; Campins, J., Aran, M., Genovés, A., Jansà, A., High impact wea